==Old English==
===Spellings===
þeġen, þeġn, þēn

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*þigna-'' ‘man, warrior’, from Indo-European ''*teke-'' ‘give birth’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[þegan]] ‘man’ (Dutch [[degen]]), Old High German [[degan]] ‘boy, servant, hero’ (German [[Degen]] ‘warrior’), Old Norse [[þegn]] ‘freeman’.

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[τέκνον]] ‘child’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'θejen/

===Noun===
'''þeġen''' ''m''
# a [[servant]]
# one serving a particular office: an [[officer]] or [[minister]]; a [[soldier]]
# a follower or companion of a great or noble man; a [[retainer]]
# one in service to the king or other superior; a [[thane]] (in later use suggesting an official title or rank)
# ''(Poetic)'': a [[man]], a [[warrior]]

